'''Richard Paul Astley''' (born 6 February 1966) is an English singer, songwriter and radio personality, who has been active in music for several decades. He gained worldwide fame in the 1980s, having multiple hits including his [[List of signature songs|signature song]] "[[Never Gonna Give You Up]]", "[[Together Forever (Rick Astley song)|Together Forever]]" and "[[Whenever You Need Somebody (song)|Whenever You Need Somebody]]", and returned to music full-time in the 2000s after a 6-year hiatus. Outside his music career, Astley has occasionally worked as a radio DJ and a podcaster.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rick Astley to join Greatest Hits Radio for special New Year's Eve show|url=https://planetradio.co.uk/greatest-hits/station/on-air/rick-astley-new-years-eve/|access-date=2022-01-05|website=Greatest Hits Radio|language=en}}</ref>

Born and raised in [[Lancashire]], Astley became a musician after leaving school, as the drummer for the soul band FBI. Three years later, he rose to fame through his association with the production trio [[Stock Aitken Waterman]]; releasing the 1987 album ''[[Whenever You Need Somebody]],'' which sold 15.2 million copies worldwide''.'' His debut single "Never Gonna Give You Up" was a number 1 hit single in 25 countries, winning the [[8th Brit Awards|1988 Brit Award]] for [[Brit Award for British Single|Best British Single]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikestockmusic.com/index.php?page=Biography02&section=sectionBiography |title=Biography |publisher=Mike Stock Music |access-date=11 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003132814/http://www.mikestockmusic.com/index.php?page=Biography02&section=sectionBiography |archive-date=3 October 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name="RickBio">[http://www.rickastley.co.uk/biography/biography.html Rickastley.com – Biography] Retrieved 28 April 2010. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210092804/http://www.rickastley.co.uk/biography/biography.html |date=10 February 2010 }}</ref> His 1988 single "Together Forever" became his second single to top the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and was one of his eight songs to reach the top ten on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. The title track was a No 1 single in seven countries, and it reached No 3 in the UK. In 1988, Astley followed-up his debut album with ''[[Hold Me in Your Arms (album)|Hold Me In Your Arms]].'' The lead single "[[She Wants to Dance with Me]]" was Astley's first single that he wrote himself, and it became a worldwide top 10 hit.

In 1991, Astley left Stock Aitken Waterman and moved his musical direction away from dance-pop and towards [[Soul music|soul]], which he explored on his albums ''[[Free (Rick Astley album)|Free]]'' (1991) and ''[[Body & Soul (Rick Astley album)|Body and Soul]]'' (1993). His 1991 single "[[Cry for Help]]" was Astley's last single to reach the top 10 in either the US or UK. In 1993, Astley retired from music to focus on spending time with his then-partner and raising their daughter. He returned to the music industry in 2000, and released the single "[[Sleeping (Rick Astley song)|Sleeping]]" and the album ''[[Keep It Turned On]]'' in 2001. Four years later, Astley released his covers album ''[[Portrait (Rick Astley album)|Portrait]].''

Astley became an [[Internet meme|Internet phenomenon]] in 2007 when the music video for his song "Never Gonna Give You Up" became integral to the [[Rickrolling]] meme,<ref>[http://www.vh1la.com/bands/az/astley_rick/bio.jhtml Rick Biografia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521113946/http://www.vh1la.com/bands/az/astley_rick/bio.jhtml |date=21 May 2009 }}. VH1 Spañol (undated). Retrieved 27 December 2006.</ref> and his performance career was revitalised by the meme's popularity. In 2010, Astley released the single "[[Lights Out (Rick Astley song)|Lights Out]]" after touring with [[Peter Kay]]. Six years later, he released his album ''[[50 (album)|50]]'' to celebrate his 50th birthday, which debuted in the UK at No.&nbsp;1.<ref name="50no1" /> He released his most recent studio album ''[[Beautiful Life (Rick Astley album)|Beautiful Life]]'' in 2018, and released his greatest hits album ''[[The Best of Me (Rick Astley album)|The Best of Me]]'' in 2019. His most recent albums were recorded at his home studio in [[Surrey]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=2 June 2020|title=Rick Astley’s best songs that aren’t ‘Never Gonna Give You Up’|url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/rick-astleys-best-songs-that-arent-never-gonna-give-you-up/|access-date=7 September 2021|website=Tone Deaf|language=en-AU}}</ref>

By the time of his brief retirement, Astley had sold approximately 40 million records worldwide.<ref>[http://www.shropshirestar.com/2008/06/07/ricks-rolling-back-the-years/ Shropshire Star.com – 7 June 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610163403/http://www.shropshirestar.com/2008/06/07/ricks-rolling-back-the-years/|date=10 June 2008}}. Retrieved 28 January 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2007/11/12/madonna-must-be-made-of-steel-but-i-was-too-sensitive-for-stardom-100252-20097466/ Liverpool Echo – 12 November 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205074602/http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2007/11/12/madonna-must-be-made-of-steel-but-i-was-too-sensitive-for-stardom-100252-20097466/|date=5 December 2008}}. Retrieved 28 January 2010.</ref> A year after the Rickrolling meme began, Astley was voted "Best Act Ever" by Internet users at the [[MTV Europe Music Awards 2008]].<ref name="bbc1">{{cite news|date=2 October 2008|title=Astley shortlisted for MTV award|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7646807.stm|url-status=live|access-date=22 November 2008|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120718155106/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7646807.stm|archive-date=18 July 2012}}</ref> His song "Never Gonna Give You Up" reached 1 billion views in July 2021, becoming the fourth 1980s song to reach this milestone (behind "[[Billie Jean]]" by [[Michael Jackson]], "[[Take On Me]]" by [[A-ha]] and "[[Sweet Child o' Mine]]" by [[Guns N' Roses]]).<ref>{{Cite web|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=29 July 2021|title=Rick Astley’s ‘Never Gonna Give You Up’ Rolls Past 1 Billion YouTube Views|url=https://variety.com/2021/digital/news/rick-astley-never-gonna-give-you-up-1-billion-youtube-views-1235030404/|access-date=6 September 2021|website=Variety|language=en-US}}</ref>

==Early life==
Astley was born on 6 February 1966 in [[Newton-le-Willows]] in [[Lancashire]], the fourth child of his family. His parents divorced when he was five and Astley was brought up by his father Horace Astley.<ref name="Independent">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/rick-astley-the-pop-idol-returns-319249.html|title=Rick Astley: The pop idol returns|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|access-date=16 May 2010|location=London|date=13 October 2005|archive-date=5 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605091222/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/rick-astley-the-pop-idol-returns-319249.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Astley remained in very close contact with his mother Cynthia Astley, who lived a few streets away from his father. After finding out that his father was the one who kicked his mother out of the house, Astley distanced himself from his father.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/978496/Rick-Astley-embarrassed-millionaire-22|title=I was embarrassed being a millionaire at just 22|last=Barber|first=Richard|date=23 June 2018|work=Daily Express|access-date=3 September 2018|archive-date=4 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052521/https://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/978496/Rick-Astley-embarrassed-millionaire-22|url-status=live}}</ref> When he was 10 years old, Astley began singing in a local church choir, which began his love of music.<ref name="LookStudio">{{cite web|url=http://lookstudio.com/rickastley/about.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020205030445/http://www.lookstudio.com/rickastley/about.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 February 2002 |title=Rick Astley – About |website=Lookstudio.com |access-date=16 May 2010 }}</ref>

During his schooldays, Astley formed and played the drums in a number of local bands, where he met guitarist [[David Morris (Conservative politician)|David Morris]].<ref name="RickBio" /><ref name="BBC12523570" /> After leaving school at sixteen, Astley was employed during the day as a driver in his father's market-gardening business and played drums on the [[Northern club circuit]] at night in bands such as Give Way – specialising in covering [[Beatles]] and [[The Shadows|Shadows]] songs – and FBI, which won several local talent competitions.<ref name="LookStudio" />

==Career==
===1985–1986: Signing with Stock Aitken Waterman===
In 1985, Astley was performing as a drummer with a soul band named FBI, with Morris on guitar. They were a well-known local band writing and performing their own music, gigging in pubs and clubs. When FBI's lead singer left the band, and Morris left to concentrate on his career in [[hairdressing]],<ref name=BBC12523570/> Astley offered to be the lead vocalist. This was when he was noticed by the record producer [[Pete Waterman]], who persuaded him to come to London to work at the [[Pete Waterman Entertainment|Pete Waterman Limited]] (PWL) recording studio,<ref name="RickBio"/> with [[RCA Records]] publishing his records. Under the tutelage of the production team of [[Mike Stock (musician)|Mike Stock]], [[Matt Aitken]] and Pete Waterman, known as [[Stock Aitken Waterman]] (SAW), Astley was taught about the [[sound recording and reproduction|recording]] process and groomed for his future career, supposedly starting off as the recording studio "[[gofer|tea boy]]". The reason for Astley to be hired as a "tape op" was to overcome his shyness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y9fNRXUoveg|title=YouTube – Rick Astley Interview in 1987 (TVam) (1987)|via=YouTube|access-date=14 May 2010|archive-date=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212081017/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y9fNRXUoveg&feature=related|url-status=live}}</ref> SAW also hired most of FBI, including Morris as a guitarist/songwriter.<ref name=BBC12523570>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12523570|title=MP David Morris on his journey from pop to politics|publisher=BBC|access-date=2 March 2011|date=2 March 2011|archive-date=15 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615141759/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12523570|url-status=live}}</ref>

===1987–1989: Success===
His first single was "When You Gonna", released as a collaboration with Lisa Fabien, and was produced by [[Phil Harding (producer)|Phil Harding]] and Ian Curnow. "We were at a stage early on with Rick, when no one knew quite what to do with him," recalled Harding. "The idea was to make him happen in the clubs... [but the song] opened up the doors for him at [[Capital London|Capitol Radio]]."<ref>{{Cite web|title=‎A Journey Through Stock Aitken Waterman: Ep 21: A Detour With Harding & Curnow Part 2 on Apple Podcasts|url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/ep-21-a-detour-with-harding-curnow-part-2/id1565879477?i=1000548034733|access-date=2022-01-17|website=Apple Podcasts|language=en-AU}}</ref> The song was released in May 1987, and with no promotion managed to chart at No. 17 in [[the Netherlands]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rick & Lisa - When You Gonna - Dutch Charts|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Rick+%26+Lisa&titel=When+You+Gonna&cat=s|website=dutchcharts.nl}}</ref> and No. 20 in [[Belgium]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rick & Lisa - When You Gonna|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/6dae/rick-&-lisa-when-you-gonna|website=ultratop.be}}</ref>

Astley's first solo offering was "[[Never Gonna Give You Up]]", recorded on New Year's Day 1987, and released eight months later, in August.<ref name="NGGYU">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3HrSN7176XI |title=YouTube – Rick Astley – Never Gonna Give You Up (1987) |via=YouTube|access-date=11 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212020403/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3HrSN7176XI |archive-date=12 February 2010 }}</ref> Although his producers were initially unenthusiastic about the track,<ref>{{Cite web |title=‎A Journey Through Stock Aitken Waterman: Ep 27: Never Gonna Give You Up on Apple Podcasts |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/ep-27-never-gonna-give-you-up/id1565879477?i=1000556095254 |access-date=2022-04-05 |website=Apple Podcasts |language=en-AU}}</ref> Astley's distinctive rich, deep voice combined with dance-pop made the song an immediate success,<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p3581|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic – Rick Astley – Overview|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=14 May 2010 }}</ref> spending five weeks at the top of the [[The Official UK Charts Company|British charts]] and becoming the year's highest-selling single. The song was also a worldwide number-one hit, topping the charts in 24 other countries, including the US, Australia, and West Germany. It was the first of 13 (worldwide) top 30 [[chart-topper|hit]] singles for him. "Never Gonna Give You Up" won Best British Single at the 1988 BPI awards (now called the ''[[BRIT Awards]]''),<ref name="talktalk" /> and he performed it in front of a global audience of 100 million.<ref name="RickBio" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YnM1Ee_H2As |title=YouTube – Rick Astley – Never Gonna Give You Up (live) 1988 |via=YouTube|access-date=17 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803233913/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YnM1Ee_H2As&gl=US&hl=en&amp;has_verified=1 |archive-date=3 August 2011 }}</ref>

Astley's next single was "[[Whenever You Need Somebody (song)|Whenever You Need Somebody]]", which was released in October. The single was a recycled Stock Aitken Waterman song, originally recorded by [[O'Chi Brown]] in 1985, which Stock says was resurrected in the rush to gather strong follow up material in the wake of Astley's unexpectedly huge global success.<ref>{{Cite web |title=‎A Journey Through Stock Aitken Waterman: Ep 29: Learning To Live (Without Your Love) to Turn It Up on Apple Podcasts |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/ep-29-learning-to-live-without-your-love-to-turn-it-up/id1565879477?i=1000559977531 |access-date=2022-05-09 |website=Apple Podcasts |language=en-AU}}</ref> It became a successful European hit, reaching No. 1 in seven countries, including West Germany and Sweden. It also reached No. 3 in the UK. It was not released in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rickastley.co.uk/discography/singles/singles02.html |title=Discography – Whenever You Need Somebody |website=Rickastley.co.uk |access-date=15 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413124135/http://www.rickastley.co.uk/discography/singles/singles02.html |archive-date=13 April 2010 }}</ref>

In November 1987, the album ''[[Whenever You Need Somebody]]'', containing four tracks written by Astley, reached number one in the UK and Australia and No. 10 in the US. It was certified 4× Platinum in the UK and Canada, and 2× Platinum in the US. ''Whenever You Need Somebody'' sold 15.2 million copies worldwide, making Astley the top-selling British act of the year.<ref name="RickBio"/>

In December 1987, Astley released a cover version of the [[Nat King Cole]] classic "[[When I Fall in Love]]". This single is mainly remembered for a closely fought contest for UK [[Christmas Number 1]]. Rivals [[EMI]], hoping to see their act the [[Pet Shop Boys]] reach No. 1, rereleased Cole's version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/take-me-to-your-heart/id277825763?i=277825791&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|title=The Ultimate Collection by Rick Astley|publisher=iTunes Store|access-date=15 May 2010|archive-date=10 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510023030/http://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/take-me-to-your-heart/id277825763?i=277825791&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rickastley.co.uk/discography/singles/singles03.html |title=Discography – When I Fall in Love |website=Rickastley.co.uk |access-date=15 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419231419/http://www.rickastley.co.uk/discography/singles/singles03.html |archive-date=19 April 2010 }}</ref> This led to a slowdown of purchases of Astley's version, allowing the Pet Shop Boys to reach the coveted top spot with their cover version of [[Always on My Mind]]. Despite selling over 200,000 copies and gaining a Silver certification from the BPI,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=Certified Awards Search |publisher=BPI |access-date=15 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924015932/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/Search.aspx |archive-date=24 September 2009 }}</ref> Astley's "When I Fall in Love" peaked in the UK at No. 2 for two weeks. The rerelease of Cole's version reached No. 4. The B side for Astley was a dance number, "[[My Arms Keep Missing You]]", which was successful in mainland Europe but wasn't released on an album until the 2002 compilation ''Greatest Hits''.

Astley's fourth single release was "[[Together Forever (Rick Astley song)|Together Forever]]" (1988), reaching No. 2 in the UK. It was denied the top spot by [[Kylie Minogue]]'s debut "[[I Should Be So Lucky]]", which reached No. 1 following her successful role as [[Charlene Robinson]] in ''[[Neighbours]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/|title=Singles Chart 12/03/88|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=15 May 2010|archive-date=26 May 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200526094853/https://www.officialcharts.com/charts//|url-status=live}}</ref> "Together Forever" was more successful in the US, topping the charts, making it his second and last US chart-topper. In 1989 Astley was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for Best New Artist but lost to [[Tracy Chapman]].

His fifth and final release from his debut album was "[[It Would Take a Strong Strong Man]]". It was a more soulful song than his other releases, and was mainly intended for the North American market. It was not released in Britain. It was another hit, reaching No. 10 on the US ''Billboard Hot 100'' and No. 1 in Canada. During the period between his debut release and his fifth single, Astley outsold every other artist in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/news/your-questions/2008/02/24/ask-rick-astley-79310-20515633/|title=Ask Rick Astley|publisher=Sunday Sun|access-date=15 May 2010|archive-date=13 September 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120913214518/http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/news/your-questions/2008/02/24/ask-rick-astley-79310-20515633/|url-status=live}}</ref> In the UK, he was in the Top 40 every week for the first six months of his career.<ref name="RickBio"/>

Production of the singer's follow up album with Stock Aitken Waterman got off to a rocky start, when a distressed Astley rejected the set's intended first single, "Nothing Can Divide Us" — a track the producers then gave to [[Jason Donovan]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=‎A Journey Through Stock Aitken Waterman: Ep 36: The Loco-Motion to Turn It Into Love on Apple Podcasts |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/ep-36-the-loco-motion-to-turn-it-into-love/id1565879477?i=1000576045102 |access-date=2022-10-01 |website=Apple Podcasts |language=en-AU}}</ref> Wishing to placate an unhappy Astley, producer [[Pete Waterman]] allowed him to start work with other writers and producers under the PWL umbrella,<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |title=‎A Journey Through Stock Aitken Waterman: Ep 39: Success to S.S. Paparazzi on Apple Podcasts |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/ep-39-success-to-s-s-paparazzi/id1565879477?i=1000580576696 |access-date=2022-10-01 |website=Apple Podcasts |language=en-AU}}</ref> but a fire in the PWL studios then destroyed much of Astley's new material,<ref name="RickBio"/> causing a delay in the release of his second album.<ref>{{Cite web |title=‎A Journey Through Stock Aitken Waterman: Ep 39: Success to S.S. Paparazzi on Apple Podcasts |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/ep-39-success-to-s-s-paparazzi/id1565879477?i=1000580576696 |access-date=2022-10-01 |website=Apple Podcasts |language=en-AU}}</ref> ''[[Hold Me in Your Arms (Rick Astley album)|Hold Me in Your Arms]]'' was released in January 1989, containing five singles, and reached No. 8 in the UK and No. 19 in the US, being certified platinum in the UK and gold in the US.

Astley's relationship with British media deteriorated significantly after the release of ''Hold Me in Your Arms'', with the media calling him a "puppet" of Stock Aitken Waterman,<ref name="talktalk">{{cite web|url=http://www.talktalk.co.uk/music/biography/artist/rick-astley/biography/10843|title=Rick Astley – Biography|publisher=TalkTalk|access-date=15 May 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2012}}</ref> although Astley had written five of his new album's tracks. The negative press affected the sales of his singles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rickastley.co.uk/discography/singles/singles09.html |title=Discography -Hold Me in Your Arms |website=Rickastley.co.uk |access-date=15 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727071046/http://www.rickastley.co.uk/discography/singles/singles09.html |archive-date=27 July 2010 }}</ref> 

The first single from the album was "[[She Wants to Dance with Me]]", written by Astley. He composed the track in the style of [[Whitney Houston]]'s hit, "[[I Wanna Dance with Somebody (Who Loves Me)|I Wanna Dance With Somebody (Who Loves Me)]]" in an effort to win the confidence of Waterman, who was a huge fan of Houston's song.<ref name=":2" /> It was another successful single, reaching No. 6 on both the UK and US charts. 

"[[Take Me to Your Heart (Rick Astley song)|Take Me to Your Heart]]" was the next single to be released from the album. It was one of four songs written and produced by Stock Aitken Waterman that were belatedly added to the album in order to help Astley make his release deadline following the fire.<ref name=":2" /> These four tracks were written and produced in just two days, with writer [[Matt Aitken]] confirming "Take Me to Your Heart" was inspired by [[house music]] act [[Inner City (band)|Inner City]]'s 1988 hit, "[[Big Fun (Inner City song)|Big Fun]]".<ref name=":2" /> The single reached No. 8 in the UK and was not released in the US. 

"[[Hold Me in Your Arms (Rick Astley song)|Hold Me in Your Arms]]", a ballad written by Astley, reached No. 10 in the UK and was also not released in North America. The next two singles released from the album were intended for the North American market. "[[Giving Up on Love]]" and a cover of [[The Temptations]] song "[[Ain't Too Proud To Beg]]" charted at No. 38 and No. 89 in the US respectively.

In December 1989, Astley set off on his first world tour, touring 15 countries including the UK, US, Australia, and Japan.<ref name="RickBio"/> By the end of the tour, he was tired of the negative press and wanted to explore alternative paths as a musician. He left Stock Aitken Waterman and RCA Records bought out his contract with PWL.

===1990–1993: Switch to soul and adult contemporary and career break===
By 1990, Astley decided to leave his dance-pop days behind him, moving towards his passion, soul. This shift in musical genre led him to change his image, ditching the [[Boy next door (stock character)|boy next door]] look, growing his hair, and presenting himself as a mature and passionate musician. His third album, ''[[Free (Rick Astley album)|Free]]'', was released in 1991 and contained collaborations with [[Elton John]].<ref name="talktalk"/> It had three singles and reached No 9 in the UK and No 31 in the US.

He achieved one more major success with his 1991 ballad "[[Cry for Help]]", which reached No 7 in both the UK and the US. The other two singles from ''Free'' were not as successful. "[[Move Right Out]]" reached No 58 in the UK and No 81 in the US, and "[[Never Knew Love (Rick Astley song)|Never Knew Love]]" reached No 70 in the UK and did not chart in the US. ''Free'' marked the end of Astley's successful period, and "Cry for Help" was the last Astley single to make the Top 10 in either the UK or US.

His next album, ''[[Body & Soul (Rick Astley album)|Body and Soul]]'', was released in 1993, and was largely an [[Adult Contemporary]] album. By the time the album was released, Astley had decided to retire from the music industry. As a result, the album did not get much promotion,<ref name="RickBio"/> not charting in the UK but managing to make the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], peaking at No 182. The two singles, "[[The Ones You Love]]" and "[[Hopelessly]]," performed very well on the US adult contemporary chart, peaking at No 19 and No 4 respectively. "The Ones You Love" peaked at No 48 in the UK but did not chart in the US. "Hopelessly" also crossed over and peaked at No 28 on the US Billboard 100, staying in the US top 40 for five weeks, and No 33 in the UK. It was the last hit to chart on the [[Top 40]] in the UK and US. It was named as one of the most performed songs at the 1994 [[Broadcast Music Incorporated|BMI Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eightiesclub.tripod.com/id229.htm |title=The Eighties Club |website=Eightiesclub.tripod.com |access-date=11 June 2013 |archive-date=14 July 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714095109/http://eightiesclub.tripod.com/id229.htm |url-status=dead }}</ref> and is one of the few songs to achieve BMI 'Million-Air' status.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chartts.tripod.com/AIR/usair1gl.htm |title=BMI Million-Airs |website=Chartts.tripod.com |access-date=11 June 2013 |archive-date=7 July 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120707064125/http://chartts.tripod.com/AIR/usair1gl.htm |url-status=live }}</ref>

===1994–2000: Retirement===
After 1993, Astley retired from the music industry at 27, deciding that family life was more important. During his time out of the music business, he raised his daughter Emilie, born in 1992.{{citation needed|date=January 2022}} For much of the 1990s and early 2000s, Astley remained out of the spotlight. He later said this was due to his growing frustration with the business side of things.<ref name="surprisecomeback">{{cite web|last1=Agius|first1=Nicola|title=Eighties legend Rick Astley, 50, wows fans – including Amanda Holden – with shock comeback single|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eighties-legend-rick-astley-50-7705932|website=Daily Mirror|access-date=8 April 2016|date=7 April 2016|archive-date=7 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407162846/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eighties-legend-rick-astley-50-7705932|url-status=live}}</ref> During this period he co-wrote "Mission Statement", a track for former [[Marillion]] singer [[Fish (singer)|Fish]]'s 1999 solo album ''[[Raingods with Zippos]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://fish-thecompany.com/int/int34.htm | title=Interview 14th May 1999 | work=Fish-TheCompany.Com: Official Site | first=Ian | last=Oakley | date=14 May 1999 | access-date=22 June 2015 | archive-date=31 January 2016 | archive-url=https://archive.today/20160131134552/http://fish-thecompany.com/int/int34.htm | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://myglobalmind.com/2014/09/12/interview-fish-vocals-fish-former-marillion/ | title=Interview with Fish (Vocals) (Fish, Former Marillion) | work=Myglobalmind Webzine | first=Duncan | last=Everson | date=12 September 2014 | access-date=22 June 2015 | archive-date=31 January 2016 | archive-url=https://archive.today/20160131134557/http://myglobalmind.com/2014/09/12/interview-fish-vocals-fish-former-marillion/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

===2000–present: Return to singing and renewed success===
Seven years after ''Body and Soul'', Astley returned to the music industry, signing a co-publishing deal with [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] and recording a new album, ''[[Keep It Turned On]]'', between November 2000 and September 2001, and released in late 2001. The album featured the single "[[Sleeping (Rick Astley song)|Sleeping]]", which became a minor club hit, thanks to a set of remixes from the US [[house music|house]] producer [[Todd Terry]]. ''Keep It Turned On'' was only released in [[Continental Europe]].<ref name="RickBio"/>

Astley's first compilation album, ''Greatest Hits'', was released in 2002, and reached No 16 on the [[UK Albums Chart]]. With no promotion from Astley, it sold over 100,000 copies and was certified Gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]].<ref name="RickBio"/> In 2003 he charted at No 10 in the UK as a songwriter with "[[Shakespeare's (Way With) Words]]" performed by short-lived boy band [[One True Voice]].

In 2004, Astley toured for the first time in 14 years, which led him to a record contract with [[Sony BMG]].<ref name="RickBio"/>

In March 2005, Astley released the album ''[[Portrait (Rick Astley album)|Portrait]]'', in which he [[cover version|covered]] many classic standards such as "[[Vincent (Don McLean song)|Vincent]]",<ref>{{cite web|format=video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ttfTJuU3frA|last=Astley|first=Rick|title=Vincent (Live)|via=YouTube|access-date=22 December 2015|archive-date=8 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208004513/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ttfTJuU3frA&app=desktop|url-status=live}}</ref> "[[Nature Boy (song)|Nature Boy]]" and "[[(They Long to Be) Close to You|Close to You]]". Astley and Sony BMG were unhappy with the result so the album was poorly promoted,<ref name="RickBio"/> yet it managed to reach No 26 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].

In April 2008, the album ''The Ultimate Collection: Rick Astley'' was released by Sony BMG, and by early May it had reached #17 on the UK Top 40 Albums Chart,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7383141.stm|work=BBC News|title=Madonna celebrates chart double|date=4 May 2008|access-date=22 May 2010|archive-date=7 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080507032234/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7383141.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> again with no promotion by Astley.

[[File:Rick Astley Tivoli Gardens.jpg|thumb|upright|Astley performing in Copenhagen, Denmark, July 2009]]

In September 2008, Astley was nominated for the 'Best Act Ever' award at the [[MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref name="bbc1" /> The push to make Astley the winner of the award continued after the announcement, as did efforts to encourage MTV to invite Astley to the awards ceremony.<ref>[http://www.bestactever.com/2008/10/10/wtf-mtv/ Bestactever.com 10 October 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014103132/http://www.bestactever.com/2008/10/10/wtf-mtv/ |date=14 October 2008 }}. Retrieved 12 October 2008.</ref> On 7 November, following a massive Internet campaign by fans, Astley won the award in Liverpool but was not there in person to receive it. [[Perez Hilton]] collected the prize on his behalf.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7714498.stm|title=US stars scoop MTV Europe awards|work=BBC News|date=7 November 2008|access-date=22 November 2008|archive-date=11 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711065539/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7714498.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> On the back of this, "Never Gonna Give You Up" (which had recently become an [[Internet meme]] via [[Rickrolling]]) returned to the UK charts, over 21 years after it was released, peaking at No 73 during the Christmas period.

During the late 2000s, Astley continued touring across the globe, touring with various other 1980s acts, such as [[Boy George]] and [[Belinda Carlisle]], in the ''[[Here and Now Tour]]''.<ref name="RickBio"/> In April 2009, he wrote an article for ''[[Time Magazine|Time]]'' about [[moot (4chan)|moot]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1894410_1893837_1894180,00.html|work=Time|title=The 2009 Time 100|date=30 April 2009|access-date=22 May 2010|archive-date=5 January 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105053232/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1894410_1893837_1894180,00.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Astley was a special guest throughout [[Peter Kay]]'s new tour, ''[[The Tour That Doesn't Tour Tour...Now On Tour]]'', from 27 April to 22 May 2010. To mark the occasion, Astley released a new single, "[[Lights Out (Rick Astley song)|Lights Out]]", on his own label on 7 June 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.famemagazine.co.uk/2010/04/28/rick-astley-returns-with-peter-kay/|title=Rick Astley Returns With Peter Kay|work=Fame Magazine|date=28 April 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221012057/http://www.famemagazine.co.uk/2010/04/28/rick-astley-returns-with-peter-kay/|archive-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> It was his first release in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in 17 years. It was well received by radio, peaking at No 15 on the UK Airplay Charts, but failed to become a commercial hit, reaching only No 97 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].

[[File:Rick Astley performing at Let's Rock Bristol, 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Astley performing at Bristol, June 2014]]

During the summer of 2010, Astley became a radio DJ for London's [[Magic Radio (London radio station)|Magic FM]], presenting a Sunday show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magic.co.uk/sectional.asp?id=38003|title=Rick Astley's Summer Soundtrack|publisher=Magic FM 105.7}}{{dead link|date=December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/05/rick-astley-magic-radio| title=Rick Astley to host Magic 105.4 Sunday show| newspaper=The Guardian| location=London| first=Josh| last=Halliday| date=5 July 2010| access-date=16 December 2016| archive-date=6 March 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306162448/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/05/rick-astley-magic-radio| url-status=live}}</ref> The initial contract was for eight weeks, but he proved popular with listeners and his contract was extended till the end of the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bauermedia.co.uk/Press-Office/News/Magic-1054-extends-Rick-Astleys-Show/ |title=Magic 105.4 Extends Rick Astley's Show  |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309050454/http://www.bauermedia.co.uk/Press-Office/News/Magic-1054-extends-Rick-Astleys-Show/ |archive-date=9 March 2012 }}</ref> In December 2010, Astley co-hosted the ''[[Chris Evans Breakfast Show]]'' on [[BBC Radio 2]] with Peter Kay,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wdf15|title=Friday – It's Kay Day!|publisher=BBC|access-date=14 December 2010|archive-date=1 August 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120801092722/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wdf15|url-status=live}}</ref> and in March 2011 appeared in [[Comic Relief]]'s [[Red Nose Day 2011|Red Nose Day]] telethon on the BBC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mn6_60oLrfI|title=The Chefs Choir Sing 'Never Gonna Give You Up' – Red Nose Day 2011|via=YouTube|access-date=29 March 2011|archive-date=22 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322044404/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mn6_60oLrfI|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTGG-Ga64V0|title=Celebrity choir sing Take That classic to wrap up Red Nose Day 2011|via=YouTube|access-date=29 March 2011|archive-date=25 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325062417/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTGG-Ga64V0|url-status=live}}</ref>

In April 2016 Astley released "[[Keep Singing]]", from his forthcoming album ''[[50 (album)|50]]''. Interviewed by [[Amanda Holden]] on the ''[[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]]'' show on 7 April, Astley explained that turning 50 had prompted him to release the single. He said, "It was a big milestone. I got back in the studio and friends were telling me the material I was working on was pretty good. So I decided to go for it."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/04/07/80s-legend-rick-astley-has-just-released-a-comeback-single-23-years-after-his-retirement-5801745 |title=Rick Astley releases comeback single Keep Singing 23 years after 'retirement' |website=Metro |location=UK |date=7 April 2016 |access-date=13 April 2016 |archive-date=11 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411145044/http://metro.co.uk/2016/04/07/80s-legend-rick-astley-has-just-released-a-comeback-single-23-years-after-his-retirement-5801745/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="surprisecomeback"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Golgowsk|first1=Nina|title=Rick Astley Releases New Single And We Swear It's Not A Rickroll|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rick-astley-releases-single_us_5706615ce4b053766188cb89|newspaper=HuffPost|access-date=8 April 2016|date=7 April 2016|archive-date=7 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407211014/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rick-astley-releases-single_us_5706615ce4b053766188cb89|url-status=live}}</ref> On 31 May, the release date for Astley's ''50'' was revealed to be 10 June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Katie |title=Rick Astley will perform and sign copies of his new album at HMV Manchester |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/rick-astley-hmv-manchester-signing--11409007 |access-date=2 June 2016 |work=men |date=31 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602042810/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/rick-astley-hmv-manchester-signing--11409007 |archive-date=2 June 2016 }}</ref> The album reached number one on the Official UK Album Sales charts in the week of 17 June 2016 to 23 June 2016.<ref name=50no1>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-36561862|title=Resurgent Rick Astley tops UK album chart|publisher=BBC|date=17 June 2016|access-date=20 June 2016|last1=Savage|first1=Mark|archive-date=19 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619235022/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-36561862|url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2016 Astley released the single "God Says / Dance", together with an official video.<ref>{{youTube|5o7WEv5Q5ZE|Rick Astley – Dance (Official Video) }}</ref>

On 1 June 2018, Astley posted a video on Twitter announcing his upcoming album ''[[Beautiful Life (Rick Astley album)|Beautiful Life]]'' set for release on 20 July.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/rickastley/status/1002505537404243969|title=Rick Astley on Twitter|website=Twitter|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} He also released a single of the same name. Astley did a tour, the ''#BeautifulLife Tour'', and tickets were first available for purchase to anyone who pre-ordered the album.<ref name=":0" /> ''Beautiful Life'' was released earlier than previously said, on 13 July 2018. The album peaked at number 6 on the UK Albums Chart.

In 2019, Astley served as the support act on [[Take That]]'s [[Greatest Hits Live (Take That)|Greatest Hits Live]] 38-date tour in Britain and Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/take-thats-greatest-hits-live-2019-tour-dates-will-be-supported-by-rick-astley__26152/|title=Take That's tour support has been announced|website=Officialcharts.com|access-date=3 June 2019|archive-date=30 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430033939/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/take-thats-greatest-hits-live-2019-tour-dates-will-be-supported-by-rick-astley__26152/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Kirwin-Jones|first=Ellie|date=11 October 2020|title=Rick Astley talks 'massive egos' after supporting Take That on tour: 'We can all pretend'|url=https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/1344796/Rick-Astley-Take-That-tour-egos-fans-Never-Gonna-Give-You-Up-news-latest-update|access-date=7 September 2021|website=Express.co.uk|language=en}}</ref> Astley is also an occasional guest vocalist at [[Foo Fighters]] concerts,<ref name="savage">{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Mark|date=24 October 2019|title=Rick Astley: Inside the home studio where he masterminded his comeback|work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50100112|access-date=25 October 2019|archive-date=24 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024151045/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50100112|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=26 Aug|first=Mike Julianelle|last2=2019|date=26 August 2019|title=Dave Grohl Rickrolls 60,000 UK Fans with Surprise Rick Astley Duet|url=https://www.thedad.com/dave-grohl-rickrolls-london-fans-with-surprise-rick-astley-duet/|access-date=7 September 2021|website=The Dad|language=en-US}}</ref> and has previously performed with [[A-ha]] and Kylie Minogue.<ref>{{Cite web|title=a-ha, Rick Astley @ Margaret Court Arena|url=https://themusic.com.au/reviews/a-ha-margaret-court-arena-cyclone/OYchLSwvLlE/24-02-20/|access-date=7 September 2021|website=The Music|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=11 September 2018|title=Watch Kylie Minogue Duet With Rick Astley On ‘Never Gonna Give You Up’|url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/watch-kylie-minogue-duet-with-rick-astley-on-never-gonna-give-you-up/|access-date=7 September 2021|website=Music Feeds}}</ref> During live performances where he sings "Never Gonna Give You Up", Astley sometimes shouts out to the audience that he is feeling "bloody marvellous" or that he is feeling "fantastic" after the line "And if you ask me how I'm feeling" to have some banter with the audience.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whitehead|first=Mat|date=21 August 2017|title=The Foo Fighters And Rick Astley Just Trolled A Whole Festival Crowd With The Perfect Rickroll|language=en-AU|work=Huffington Post|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/2017/08/21/the-foo-fighters-and-rick-astley-just-trolled-a-whole-festival-crowd-with-the-perfect-rickroll_a_23155255/|access-date=7 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Johnson|first=Helen|date=20 August 2017|title=Rick Astley did a sweary 'Never Gonna Give You Up' with the Foo Fighters|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/rick-astley-sweary-never-gonna-13504620|access-date=7 September 2021|website=Manchester Evening News|language=en}}</ref>

On 12 October 2019, Astley appeared on ''[[CBeebies Bedtime Stories]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=CBeebies Bedtime Stories Catch up CBEEBIES. Watch all episodes from "CBeebies Bedtime Stories" on demand. Catchupplayer.co.uk|url=https://www.catchupplayer.co.uk/episode/137657/Cbeebies_Bedtime_Stories.html|access-date=2021-09-15|website=www.catchupplayer.co.uk|language=en}}</ref>

On 25 October 2019, Astley released a new album, ''[[The Best of Me (Rick Astley album)|The Best of Me]]'', which includes some of his original tracks, some reimagined versions of his existing songs, and the new single "[[Every One of Us (song)|Every One of Us]]". One of the reimagined songs is a pianoforte version of "Never Gonna Give You Up", in which Astley changes the key to F minor. In live concerts, Astley sings it in A minor.<ref>{{Citation|title=Rick Astley – Never Gonna Give You Up (Pianoforte) (Official Audio)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GHMjD0Lp5DY|access-date=25 October 2019|archive-date=26 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126214410/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GHMjD0Lp5DY|url-status=live}}</ref>

In June 2020, towards the end of [[COVID-19 lockdowns|the nationwide lockdown]] in England due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], Astley released four cover songs; "[[Ain't No Sunshine]]" by [[Bill Withers]], "[[Everlong]]" by Foo Fighters, "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]" by [[David Guetta]] and "[[Better Now]]" by [[Post Malone]]. Around this time, Astley made a [[TikTok]] account, launching it with a video of him dancing to "Never Gonna Give You Up" which received millions of views.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rick Astley rickrolls TikTok, scores millions of views|url=https://www.owensbororadio.com/2020/11/05/rick-astley-rickrolls-tiktok-scores-millions-of-views/|date=5 November 2020|access-date=7 September 2021|website=Owensboro Radio|language=en}}</ref>

On 30 November 2020, Astley released a single, "Love This Christmas", the video featuring Astley performing amid a flurry of [[snow]] and dancing [[Snowman|snowmen]]. To accompany the single, Astley launched a signed limited edition Christmas card, with all proceeds going to the [[Shooting Star Children's Hospices|Shooting Stars Children's Hospices]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=11 December 2020|title=Rick Astley returns with new single Love This Christmas|url=https://www.classicpopmag.com/2020/12/rick-astley-returns-with-new-single-love-this-christmas/|access-date=1 January 2021|website=Classic Pop Magazine|language=en-US|archive-date=17 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117051348/https://www.classicpopmag.com/2020/12/rick-astley-returns-with-new-single-love-this-christmas/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 16 March 2021, Astley recorded a cover of [[the Temptations]] song "[[My Girl (The Temptations song)|My Girl]]".

On 7 April 2021, Astley released a single, "Unwanted", inspired by the era and vibes of the original podcast.<ref>{{Citation|title=Rick Astley - Unwanted (Official Song from the Podcast) (Lyric Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lU1EmTA4J60|access-date=8 April 2021|archive-date=8 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210408170636/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lU1EmTA4J60|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 28 July 2021, "Never Gonna Give You Up" hit one billion views on YouTube, making Astley the fourth 1980s artist to pass this milestone, after [[Michael Jackson]], [[A-ha]] and [[Guns N' Roses]]. Astley celebrated by releasing a new limited-edition, signed, numbered and coloured 7" vinyl single of "Never Gonna Give You Up", backed with the pianoforte version from ''The Best of Me.''

On 2 September 2021, amid the news that [[ABBA]] have reunited, Astley released a cover of their song "[[The Winner Takes It All]]".<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rick Astley's stunning cover of ABBA's 'The Winner Takes it All' will give you goosebumps - video|url=https://www.smoothradio.com/artists/abba/rick-astley-winner-takes-it-all-cover-video/|access-date=4 September 2021|website=Smooth|language=en}}</ref>

On 14 September 2021, Astley announced he would be collaborating with the indie band [[Blossoms (band)|Blossoms]] to perform songs by [[The Smiths]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=2021-09-14|title=Blossoms and Rick Astley to perform The Songs of The Smiths|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-58557011|access-date=2021-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Rick Astley and Blossoms to perform songs of The Smiths live|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/19580535.rick-astley-blossoms-perform-songs-smiths-live/|access-date=2021-09-14|website=The Bolton News|language=en}}</ref>

==Rickrolling internet phenomenon==
{{Main|Rickrolling}}
[[File:Rick Astley Macy Parade cropped.jpg|thumb|Astley rickrolling the 2008 [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]]]]
In 2007,<!--EDITORS PLEASE READ. THE RICKROLL INTERNET MEME BEGAN IN 2007, PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THE DATE TO 2008 BECAUSE THIS IS NOT ACCURATE.--><ref name="Date">{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/trends?q=rick+astley%2C+rickroll%2C+rick+roll%2C+never+gonna+give+you+up&ctab=0&geo=all&date=2007&sort=0|title=Rick Roll related Google Trends|publisher=[[Google Trends]]|access-date=4 April 2008}}</ref> Astley became the subject of a [[viral phenomenon|viral]] [[Internet meme]] known as [[rickrolling]]. The meme is a type of [[bait and switch]] using a disguised [[hyperlink]] that leads to the ''Never Gonna Give you Up ''music video. When victims click on a seemingly unrelated link, the site with the music video loads instead of what was expected, and in doing so they are said to have been "Rickrolled". The meme has also extended to using the song's lyrics in unexpected places. The meme gained mainstream attention in 2008 through several publicized events, particularly when [[YouTube]] used it on its 2008 April Fools' Day event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2008/03/31/youtube-rickrolls-users/|title=YouTube RickRolls Users|publisher=[[TechCrunch]]|access-date=1 June 2008|archive-date=29 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829200506/http://techcrunch.com/2008/03/31/youtube-rickrolls-users/|url-status=live}}</ref> Rickrolling saw a massive resurgence online in the early 2020s. In online classes on [[Zoom (software)|Zoom]] during the worldwide [[COVID-19 lockdowns|COVID-19 lockdown]], students often rickrolled their classmates and teachers.<ref>{{Cite web|title=You Can Now 'Rick Roll' Your Zoom Meetings|url=https://nerdist.com/article/you-can-now-rick-roll-your-zoom-meetings/|access-date=4 March 2021|website=Nerdist}}</ref> A 4K remaster of the "Never Gonna Give You Up" music video went viral in early 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|date=18 February 2021|title=Rick Astley's Rick Roll meme goes viral again with disturbing 4K remaster|url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/rick-astleys-rick-roll-meme-goes-viral-again-with-disturbing-4k-remaster-1517065/|access-date=4 March 2021|website=Dexerto|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=18 February 2021|title=Rickroll your eyeballs into oblivion with remastered "Never Gonna Give You Up": Watch|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2021/02/rick-astley-never-gonna-give-you-up-remastered/|access-date=4 March 2021|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US}}</ref>

Initially, Astley, who had only recently returned to performing after a 10-year hiatus, was hesitant about using his newfound popularity from the meme to further his career, but accepted the fame when he Rickrolled the 2008 [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] with a surprise performance of the song. Since then, Astley has seen his performance career revitalised by the meme's popularity. In an interview, Astley stated that one of his favourite Rickroll videos is "BarackRoll", a rickroll featuring clips from rallies by [[Barack Obama]] during his [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|2008 presidential campaign]], edited to make it look as though he is singing "Never Gonna Give You Up".<ref>{{Cite web|last=News|first=Taiwan|title=Astley never stops appreciating 'Never Gonna Give You Up' {{!}} Taiwan News {{!}} 22 October 2016 00:36:32|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3004212|access-date=7 September 2021|website=Taiwan News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Video Pick: Obama 'Sings' Rick Astley's Hit|language=en-US|work=Wired|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/08/obamas-never-go/|access-date=7 September 2021|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=20 October 2008|title=The Rickroll Gets Political|url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/19914/rickroll-gets-political|access-date=7 September 2021|website=www.mentalfloss.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=metrowebukmetro|date=9 October 2008|title=John McCain Gets BarackRoll'd|url=https://metro.co.uk/2008/10/09/john-mccain-gets-barackrolld-9229/|access-date=7 September 2021|website=Metro|language=en}}</ref>

Astley himself has been rickrolled a few times; in fact, the first time he was rickrolled actually pre-dated the viral phenomenon. In an interview with [[Larry King]], Astley stated that the first time he fell for the prank was through an email his friend sent him during the early 2000s.<ref name=":03">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L0HVnaIRrFo |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211212/L0HVnaIRrFo| archive-date=2021-12-12 |url-status=live|title=Has Rick Astley ever been "Rick-rolled"?|date=25 January 2017|access-date=29 September 2020|work=[[Larry King Now]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}{{cbignore}}</ref> On a [[Reddit]] post in June 2020, a user claimed to have met Astley backstage when they were 12 years old, but the user posted a link to the song instead of a picture verifying the encounter. Astley later confirmed he had been tricked into clicking the link.<ref>{{Cite web|title=New Internet Legend Manages to Rick Roll Rick Astley|url=https://news.yahoo.com/internet-legend-manages-rick-roll-143025415.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200621105834/https://news.yahoo.com/internet-legend-manages-rick-roll-143025415.html|archive-date=21 June 2020|access-date=18 June 2020}}</ref><ref name="time_NewI2">{{Cite web|author=Melissa Locker|date=18 June 2020|title=New Internet Legend Manages to Rick Roll Rick Astley|url=https://time.com/5855001/rick-roll-rick-astley/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200618192603/https://time.com/5855001/rick-roll-rick-astley/|archive-date=18 June 2020|access-date=19 June 2020|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|quote=The trick was so seamlessly perfect that Astley had no choice but to applaud it by posting a clap emoji, and then called out the clever user in his sign off post, saying, "u/theMalleableDuck I salute you!"}}</ref> The post became the most upvoted post of 2020 on Reddit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcin|first1=Tim|date=8 December 2020|title=Rick Astley getting rickrolled was Reddit's most upvoted post in 2020|publisher=Mashable|url=https://mashable.com/article/reddit-rick-astley-rickrolled-top-post/|access-date=9 February 2021}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Astley has been married to film producer Lene Bausager since 2003.<ref name="bbc">{{cite web |last1=Savage |first1=Mark |title=Rick Astley on his wife Lene: 'The success I'm having is due to her' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-45082037 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=7 August 2018 |access-date=9 April 2021 |archive-date=7 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201107234326/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-45082037 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":1" /> They have a daughter who has a master's degree in fine art and is a garden designer.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|last=Rocca|first=Jane|date=22 August 2020|title='I fell in love with her the day I met her': the women in Rick Astley's life|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/i-fell-in-love-with-her-the-day-i-met-her-the-women-in-rick-astley-s-life-20200819-p55n8s.html|access-date=4 September 2021|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en}}</ref> Astley met Bausager when she was working as a promoter with RCA in 1987,<ref name="Independent"/> and she is now a film producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalhit.com/galleries/22/1/29|title=Photo 29 Lene Bausager and Rick Astley &#124; 78th Annual Academy Awards|website=Digitalhit.com|access-date=22 May 2010|archive-date=29 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729115917/http://www.digitalhit.com/galleries/22/1/29|url-status=live}}</ref> He and his wife live in the Surrey town of [[Molesey]], and his daughter lives in Denmark.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rick-astley-interview-the-1980s-pop-star-on-diy-disasters-and-why-hes-never-gonna-get-into-gardening-vh7ccb32v|title=Rick Astley interview: the 1980s pop star on DIY disasters and why he's never gonna get into gardening|first=Hugh|last=Graham|date=21 October 2018|website=The Times|access-date=27 April 2019|archive-date=24 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024040521/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rick-astley-interview-the-1980s-pop-star-on-diy-disasters-and-why-hes-never-gonna-get-into-gardening-vh7ccb32v|url-status=live}}</ref> He maintains a home recording studio and has a collection of guitars.<ref name="savage"/>

